## 4. The 5-Stage LLM Pipeline

This is the heart of the project. The pipeline runs **sequentially** — each stage consumes the output of the previous one. Every stage has a designated primary LLM and a fallback LLM that activates automatically on failure.

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    IN(["🎤 INPUT\nartist + title?"])

    subgraph S1["Stage 1 · Analysis"]
        direction TB
        P1["Primary: Google\nGemini 1.5 Flash"]
        F1["Fallback: Mistral Medium"]
        OPT1["temp=0.7 · max=1500t"]
    end

    subgraph S2["Stage 2 · Refinement"]
        direction TB
        P2["Primary: Mistral Medium"]
        F2["Fallback: Google Gemini"]
        OPT2["temp=0.5 · max=1200t"]
    end

    subgraph S3["Stage 3 · Enhancement"]
        direction TB
        P3["Primary: DeepSeek Chat"]
        F3["Fallback: Claude 3 Haiku"]
        OPT3["temp=0.8 · max=1200t"]
    end

    subgraph S4["Stage 4 · Quality Control"]
        direction TB
        P4["Primary: Claude 3 Haiku"]
        F4["Fallback: GPT-4o Mini"]
        OPT4["temp=0.4 · max=1000t"]
    end

    subgraph S5["Stage 5 · Finalization"]
        direction TB
        P5["Primary: GPT-4o Mini"]
        F5["Fallback: Claude 3 Haiku"]
        OPT5["temp=0.3 · max=500t"]
    end

    VAL(["✅ Validator\n&lt;400 chars · no names\nEnglish · clean"])
    OUT(["🎼 OUTPUT\nSuno-ready prompt"])

    IN --> S1 --> S2 --> S3 --> S4 --> S5 --> VAL --> OUT
```

### Stage-by-Stage Detail

---

#### 🟦 Stage 1 — Analysis
**Provider:** Google Gemini 1.5 Flash → *fallback:* Mistral Medium  
**Temperature:** 0.7 · **Max Tokens:** 1500  
**Input:** Raw `{artist, title?}` from user  
**Goal:** Generate a detailed musical DNA analysis of the artist/track.

Two prompt modes:
- **Artist + Title:** Analyzes the specific song — genre, subgenre, rhythm, melody, harmony, instrumentation, production style, BPM, vocal style, emotional tone.
- **Artist Only:** Analyzes the artist's entire catalog — primary genres, evolution, signature elements, production characteristics, BPM ranges, innovations.

> **Critical rule:** The analysis must never mention the artist name or song title.

**Output:** ~1000–1500 token free-form musical analysis in prose.

---

#### 🟩 Stage 2 — Refinement
**Provider:** Mistral Medium → *fallback:* Google Gemini  
**Temperature:** 0.5 · **Max Tokens:** 1200  
**Input:** Stage 1 prose analysis  
**Goal:** Structure the analysis into 6 technical categories.

Forced output structure:
```
1. GENRE & STYLE
2. RHYTHM & TEMPO
3. INSTRUMENTATION
4. PRODUCTION
5. HARMONIC STRUCTURE
6. MELODIC ELEMENTS
```

Lower temperature (0.5) makes this stage more deterministic and structured.  
**Output:** Organized, technical, category-tagged musical description.

---

#### 🟧 Stage 3 — Enhancement
**Provider:** DeepSeek Chat → *fallback:* Claude 3 Haiku  
**Temperature:** 0.8 · **Max Tokens:** 1200  
**Input:** Stage 2 structured categories  
**Goal:** Add creative, evocative, AI-generator-friendly language.

Operations:
- Atmospheric and emotional descriptors
- Textural and sonic imagery vocabulary
- Production terminology AI generators respond well to
- Dynamic and energy-level descriptions

Higher temperature (0.8) maximizes creativity.  
**Output:** Vibrant, expressive, paint-a-sonic-picture description.

---

#### 🟥 Stage 4 — Quality Control
**Provider:** Claude 3 Haiku → *fallback:* GPT-4o Mini  
**Temperature:** 0.4 · **Max Tokens:** 1000  
**Input:** Stage 3 enhanced description  
**Goal:** Polish, prune, verify technical accuracy.

QC checklist applied:
- Eliminate redundancy
- Verify BPM realism
- Confirm genre accuracy
- Check instrumentation clarity
- Ensure logical flow
- Remove ambiguity

Lower temperature (0.4) for precise, editorial behavior.  
**Output:** Clean, professional, accurate musical description.

---

#### 🟪 Stage 5 — Finalization
**Provider:** GPT-4o Mini → *fallback:* Claude 3 Haiku  
**Temperature:** 0.3 · **Max Tokens:** 500  
**Input:** Stage 4 polished description  
**Goal:** Compress everything into a ≤400 char Suno AI prompt.

Hard constraints injected into the prompt:
```
- Maximum 400 characters including spaces
- NO artist names or song titles
- English language only
- Focus on arrangement, style, BPM, musical elements
- Return ONLY the final prompt, nothing else
```

Lowest temperature (0.3) for maximum constraint compliance.  
**Output:** The raw final prompt string (≤400 chars, ready for Suno).

---

## 5. Data Flow — Step by Step

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    actor User
    participant SPA as Browser SPA
    participant API as /api/generate
    participant PP as PromptPipeline
    participant LLM as LLMProviderManager
    participant VAL as PromptValidator
    participant LOG as Logger

    User->>SPA: Enter artist [+ title] → click Generate
    SPA->>API: POST {artist, title}
    API->>API: Validate input (artist required)
    API->>PP: validatePipeline()
    PP-->>API: {ready, missing[], available[]}
    
    alt Pipeline not ready
        API-->>SPA: 503 + missing providers list
    end

    API->>LOG: logPipelineStart()
    API->>PP: processInput(artist, title)

    loop Stages 1–5
        PP->>LLM: makeRequest(provider, prompt, options)
        alt Primary succeeds
            LLM-->>PP: response text
        else Primary fails
            PP->>LOG: logStageError()
            PP->>LOG: logFallbackUsed()
            PP->>LLM: makeRequest(fallback, prompt, options)
            LLM-->>PP: response text
        end
        PP->>LOG: logStageSuccess()
    end

    PP-->>API: results {stages[], finalPrompt}
    API->>VAL: validatePrompt(finalPrompt, artist, title)
    
    alt Validation fails
        API->>VAL: cleanPrompt() → truncateIntelligently()
        VAL-->>API: cleaned prompt
        API->>VAL: validatePrompt() again
    end

    API->>LOG: logPipelineComplete() + logValidationResult()
    API-->>SPA: Full JSON response (pipeline stages + final prompt + validation)
    SPA->>User: Display prompt + stage-by-stage breakdown
```

