## 13. Error Handling & Fallback Strategy

The pipeline uses a **two-tier resilience model** at every stage:

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    TRY["Try Primary Provider"] --> OK{Success?}
    OK -->|Yes| NEXT["Pass output to next stage"]
    OK -->|No| LOG_ERR["Log error (logStageError)"]
    LOG_ERR --> HASFB{Has fallback?}
    HASFB -->|No| THROW["Throw: Stage N failed"]
    HASFB -->|Yes| LOG_FB["Log fallback activation"]
    LOG_FB --> TRY_FB["Try Fallback Provider"]
    TRY_FB --> OK2{Success?}
    OK2 -->|Yes| NEXT
    OK2 -->|No| THROW2["Throw original primary error"]
```

**Fallback matrix:**

| Stage | Primary | Fallback |
|---|---|---|
| 1 · Analysis | Google | Mistral |
| 2 · Refinement | Mistral | Google |
| 3 · Enhancement | DeepSeek | Anthropic |
| 4 · Quality | Anthropic | OpenAI |
| 5 · Finalization | OpenAI | Anthropic |

Note: DeepSeek and Mistral are strictly optional (`🟡`), so if Stage 2 or 3 fail and their fallbacks also fail, the whole pipeline throws. For maximum reliability, all 6 providers should be configured.

At the HTTP layer, `routes/generate.js` wraps everything in a try/catch and returns structured 500 responses with `error.stack` in dev mode only.

---

## 14. Cost & Performance Reference

### Estimated Costs per 1000 Requests

| Provider | Estimated Cost | Stage Used |
|---|---|---|
| Google Gemini 1.5 Flash | ~$0.50–1.00 | Stage 1 |
| Mistral Medium | ~$0.50–1.00 | Stage 2 |
| DeepSeek Chat | ~$0.10–0.50 | Stage 3 |
| Claude 3 Haiku | ~$1.00–2.00 | Stage 4 |
| GPT-4o Mini | ~$2.00–5.00 | Stage 5 |
| **Total (5 stages)** | **~$4.10–9.50** | — |

### Performance Characteristics

- Each external LLM call has a **60-second timeout**
- A full 5-stage run typically takes **15–60 seconds** depending on provider latency
- The `PIPELINE_TIMEOUT_MS=180000` (3 min) sets the upper bound
- No caching is implemented — every request makes 5 fresh LLM calls
- Recommendation for production: add Redis caching keyed on `{artist, title}`

> **Bottleneck:** Stage 1 (Google Gemini) and Stage 4 (Anthropic) tend to be slowest due to their larger output token budgets.

